[{"sha":"f7505ea3decf94911dcab609e8582bba8cc07701","author":{"name":"Kaixi Hou","email":"edaff5a4cab35408d68c643283259ec28622ef39@nvidia.com"},"message":"Use CudnnRNNV3 APIs","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/f7505ea3decf94911dcab609e8582bba8cc07701"},{"sha":"4dadd1262353df4671b43f8275f3d03129bbb973","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Move schema version into micro_interpreter.h

This is a first (somewhat non-intuitive) step towards being able to use
clang as part of the github CI system.

The benefits of this refactor are that we avoid a dependency into
tensorflow/core which reduces the number of files that need to be
downloaded as part of a bazel build from a TFLM CI docker image.

The tflite schema version has been unchanged since at-least Oct 2018
(when tflite was moved out of tensorflow/contrib).

Progress towards preventing a repeat of https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues/46415","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/4dadd1262353df4671b43f8275f3d03129bbb973"},{"sha":"83cc821a93ffee94be832ef99111a60aeb649067","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Update the TFLM CI docs based on the new way to build a docker image.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/njzjz/tensorflow/commits/83cc821a93ffee94be832ef99111a60aeb649067"},{"sha":"c40f3eacebfc208123ab9ceaf750d6abf4632abb","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Do not mark ops that are supported with constant folding for outside compilation

These ops are supported on TPU through constant folding which may depend on the inputs shapes not known at the time of marking ops for outside compilation. Such ops may not have any legalization or canonicalization patterns but shouldn't be marked for outside compilation.

We can remove this manual list once we support constant folding and shape inference using the host side computation while legalizing these ops to HLO.

[{"sha":"3c281192c37519580d4aeeba02b58923d8edc809","author":{"name":"j-bernardi","email":"c7fb1083a8e0e494f05049af5d8c1b0768ef2e84@gmail.com"},"message":"Adding multi_dim to class_weight option in fit()

Currently, model.fit(class_weight={}) only works if y_data is of
rank 2 in the output, e.g. (batch_size,) or (batch_size, N_one_hot)
(if N==1, squeeze).

This change adds a flag `class_weight_mode`="multi_dim" to
`model.compile()` that allows dense labels of any shape to be compatible
with `class_weight` in `model.fit()`, asserting that they are either
one_hot encoded or in dense representation with an expanded final
dimension. E.g. necessary for image segmentation or temporal / sequence
data. The relevant tests are included for the DataHandler.

Also adding test that class weight is a dict, and testing existing
class_weight functionality","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/j-bernardi/tensorflow/commits/3c281192c37519580d4aeeba02b58923d8edc809"}]

[{"sha":"4db28856db1f9e8c0a062beea5fa5f8774c21663","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Explicitly reject ops with symbol ref attributes in the fallback legalization pass

We don't attempt legalization for ops with symbol reference attribute even if they are in allow-list. Xla op kernels for these ops compile the function to HLO on-demand which won't work in our case as it may contain unsupported ops in the fallback nor we provide XlaCompiler to the kernel. Also, these patterns are used from a function pass.

This is just an extra check which might be useful if we switch to deny list instead of allow list or avoid crashing if an op with symbol ref is added to the allow list.

Change-Id: I6caf0b5940934a3a90737f7fae288c42953a23f1","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/huaxz1986/tensorflow/commits/754034e5de084cdb92a01a0d4e06fbce06b9723d"},{"sha":"3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec","author":{"name":"Andrew Audibert","email":"23f2b5dd93c922fa4b806faa35ad0644038a966e@google.com"},"message":"[tf.data service] Support num_consumers being a Tensor.

The `if num_consumers >= 0:` check causes an error when num_consumers is a Tensor in graph mode:

OperatorNotAllowedInGraphError: using a `tf.Tensor` as a Python `bool` is not allowed in Graph execution

Comparing to `None` accomplishes the same thing without this issue. Once the forward compatibility window expires we can remove the check completely.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 351894589
Change-Id: I0f6e8b93f6ae14b92b08c7c438d6a111ae0efff7","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/huaxz1986/tensorflow/commits/3c80be9f2cfece929f5858e7df0e7f4503c9baec"},{"sha":"14d708ab72f36aa8ab69493e2474e475b5107bfa","author":{"name":"Bixia Zheng","email":"4733e76aa05f451fa375889c85b599266aa9962f@google.com"},"message":"[TF:TRT] Handle out of GPU memory when creating TensorRT execution context.

Previously, we use ICudaEngine::createExecutionContext to create a TensorRT
execution context along with the GPU needed to execute the Cuda Engine. This
API doesn't handle out of GPU memory properly, instead propagates an exception.
This change uses ICudaEngine::createExecutionContextWithoutDeviceMemory to
create a TensorRT execution context without any GPU memory, and let TF-TRT
create the needed GPU memory. In order to keep track of such GPU memory, we
wrap the TensorRT execution context and the associated GPU memory in a new
class callsed ExecutionContext.

Change-Id: Ib946396339e4bc16dba62501e75bddf1fd361c01","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/huaxz1986/tensorflow/commits/a18d8e62765a3b6b21cd16e19094f1cad0be9c2e"},{"sha":"6983bacea1beb7c1e83cb1416b0320d935aa57b9","author":{"name":"Tayo Oguntebi","email":"6a4aa867bc243a7c80630f0a0484e62aa84e97c5@google.com"},"message":"Enables per-host dummy args for TPUExecute (TF1) and adds XLA options.

Enabling this logic removes cross-worker send/recv dependencies required for TPUExecuteOp nodes to access a model's variables. This decreases overhead at the start of a training loop.

The approach used is to replace remote variable reads with zero tensors on each worker, except for the primary worker. The zero tensors feed TPUExecute nodes that are local to that worker.  For large distributed systems with large variables, this removes the need for the initial Send/Recv variable broadcast, which can be expensive.

clang as part of the github CI system.

The benefits of this refactor are that we avoid a dependency into
tensorflow/core which reduces the number of files that need to be
downloaded as part of a bazel build from a TFLM CI docker image.

The tflite schema version has been unchanged since at-least Oct 2018

Progress towards preventing a repeat of https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues/46415","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/melG81/tensorflow/commits/4dadd1262353df4671b43f8275f3d03129bbb973"},{"sha":"83cc821a93ffee94be832ef99111a60aeb649067","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Update the TFLM CI docs based on the new way to build a docker image.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/melG81/tensorflow/commits/83cc821a93ffee94be832ef99111a60aeb649067"},{"sha":"c40f3eacebfc208123ab9ceaf750d6abf4632abb","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Do not mark ops that are supported with constant folding for outside compilation

These ops are supported on TPU through constant folding which may depend on the inputs shapes not known at the time of marking ops for outside compilation. Such ops may not have any legalization or canonicalization patterns but shouldn't be marked for outside compilation.

We can remove this manual list once we support constant folding and shape inference using the host side computation while legalizing these ops to HLO.

PiperOrigin-RevId: 352064455
Change-Id: Iefda92654fa73d12ab213abe7ea13e0007201f95","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/pedro-r-marques/tensorflow/commits/102e1f98552c4fe32a9abbb82ed22275f1be161b"},{"sha":"4db28856db1f9e8c0a062beea5fa5f8774c21663","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Explicitly reject ops with symbol ref attributes in the fallback legalization pass

We don't attempt legalization for ops with symbol reference attribute even if they are in allow-list. Xla op kernels for these ops compile the function to HLO on-demand which won't work in our case as it may contain unsupported ops in the fallback nor we provide XlaCompiler to the kernel. Also, these patterns are used from a function pass.

This is just an extra check which might be useful if we switch to deny list instead of allow list or avoid crashing if an op with symbol ref is added to the allow list.

Change-Id: I5f66d4db72718761364d7ee9336dbd27afe3801d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/pedro-r-marques/tensorflow/commits/ed73ad7d461e0ced46ab66cd18400124223d2afd"},{"sha":"c40f3eacebfc208123ab9ceaf750d6abf4632abb","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Do not mark ops that are supported with constant folding for outside compilation

These ops are supported on TPU through constant folding which may depend on the inputs shapes not known at the time of marking ops for outside compilation. Such ops may not have any legalization or canonicalization patterns but shouldn't be marked for outside compilation.

We can remove this manual list once we support constant folding and shape inference using the host side computation while legalizing these ops to HLO.

This is a first (somewhat non-intuitive) step towards being able to use
clang as part of the github CI system.

The benefits of this refactor are that we avoid a dependency into
tensorflow/core which reduces the number of files that need to be
downloaded as part of a bazel build from a TFLM CI docker image.

The tflite schema version has been unchanged since at-least Oct 2018
(when tflite was moved out of tensorflow/contrib).

Progress towards preventing a repeat of https://github.com/tensorflow/tensorflow/issues/46415","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/4dadd1262353df4671b43f8275f3d03129bbb973"},{"sha":"83cc821a93ffee94be832ef99111a60aeb649067","author":{"name":"Advait Jain","email":"381329857d3dce0cdb28ee10c109de30b1dd6745@users.noreply.github.com"},"message":"Update the TFLM CI docs based on the new way to build a docker image.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/xiaohanhuang/tensorflow/commits/83cc821a93ffee94be832ef99111a60aeb649067"},{"sha":"c40f3eacebfc208123ab9ceaf750d6abf4632abb","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Do not mark ops that are supported with constant folding for outside compilation

These ops are supported on TPU through constant folding which may depend on the inputs shapes not known at the time of marking ops for outside compilation. Such ops may not have any legalization or canonicalization patterns but shouldn't be marked for outside compilation.

We can remove this manual list once we support constant folding and shape inference using the host side computation while legalizing these ops to HLO.

[{"sha":"4db28856db1f9e8c0a062beea5fa5f8774c21663","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Explicitly reject ops with symbol ref attributes in the fallback legalization pass

We don't attempt legalization for ops with symbol reference attribute even if they are in allow-list. Xla op kernels for these ops compile the function to HLO on-demand which won't work in our case as it may contain unsupported ops in the fallback nor we provide XlaCompiler to the kernel. Also, these patterns are used from a function pass.

This is just an extra check which might be useful if we switch to deny list instead of allow list or avoid crashing if an op with symbol ref is added to the allow list.

These ops are supported on TPU through constant folding which may depend on the inputs shapes not known at the time of marking ops for outside compilation. Such ops may not have any legalization or canonicalization patterns but shouldn't be marked for outside compilation.

We can remove this manual list once we support constant folding and shape inference using the host side computation while legalizing these ops to HLO.

These ops are supported on TPU through constant folding which may depend on the inputs shapes not known at the time of marking ops for outside compilation. Such ops may not have any legalization or canonicalization patterns but shouldn't be marked for outside compilation.

We can remove this manual list once we support constant folding and shape inference using the host side computation while legalizing these ops to HLO.

[{"sha":"4db28856db1f9e8c0a062beea5fa5f8774c21663","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Explicitly reject ops with symbol ref attributes in the fallback legalization pass

We don't attempt legalization for ops with symbol reference attribute even if they are in allow-list. Xla op kernels for these ops compile the function to HLO on-demand which won't work in our case as it may contain unsupported ops in the fallback nor we provide XlaCompiler to the kernel. Also, these patterns are used from a function pass.

This is just an extra check which might be useful if we switch to deny list instead of allow list or avoid crashing if an op with symbol ref is added to the allow list.

Change-Id: I5f66d4db72718761364d7ee9336dbd27afe3801d","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/mark0725/tensorflow/commits/ed73ad7d461e0ced46ab66cd18400124223d2afd"},{"sha":"c40f3eacebfc208123ab9ceaf750d6abf4632abb","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Do not mark ops that are supported with constant folding for outside compilation

These ops are supported on TPU through constant folding which may depend on the inputs shapes not known at the time of marking ops for outside compilation. Such ops may not have any legalization or canonicalization patterns but shouldn't be marked for outside compilation.

We can remove this manual list once we support constant folding and shape inference using the host side computation while legalizing these ops to HLO.

clang as part of the github CI system.

The benefits of this refactor are that we avoid a dependency into
tensorflow/core which reduces the number of files that need to be
downloaded as part of a bazel build from a TFLM CI docker image.

The tflite schema version has been unchanged since at-least Oct 2018
(when tflite was moved out of tensorflow/contrib).

[{"sha":"311e92b1895dfb2a6c4701f4faf93803e2949145","author":{"name":"Andrew Or","email":"a5c478d606458f6c868a5126471748acd4730a6f@gmail.com"},"message":"Add support for heterogeneous training (round 1)

This commit adds support for uneven sharding and data processing.
This is achieved independently on each worker by skipping over
examples that are not assigned to it. The ratio of how much data
to assign to the workers in each batch is specified through a
variable we call "heterogeneous split". For e.g., 12,3,2 means
the global batch size is 17 (12+3+2) and there are three workers.
The first worker is assigned 12 examples in each batch, the
second worker is assigned 3, and the third worker 2. This means
the first worker will process examples [0-12) in the first batch,
[17-29) in the second batch and so on.

The changes here assume the dataset will be batched (after
sharding) by the per-worker batch size instead of the global
batch size. The per-worker batch is then split among the replicas
on the worker by the multi-device iterator as before. More
specifically, the rebatching that happens in DistributedIterator
is now for splitting the per-worker batch into one or more
per-replica batches.","distinct":true,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/andrewor14/tensorflow/commits/311e92b1895dfb2a6c4701f4faf93803e2949145"}]

Change-Id: Iefda92654fa73d12ab213abe7ea13e0007201f95","distinct":false,"url":"https://api.github.com/repos/advaitjain/tensorflow/commits/102e1f98552c4fe32a9abbb82ed22275f1be161b"},{"sha":"4db28856db1f9e8c0a062beea5fa5f8774c21663","author":{"name":"Smit Hinsu","email":"0f9dce5f2da36d8473ff9a50fbb0e06a148c5fae@google.com"},"message":"Explicitly reject ops with symbol ref attributes in the fallback legalization pass

We don't attempt legalization for ops with symbol reference attribute even if they are in allow-list. Xla op kernels for these ops compile the function to HLO on-demand which won't work in our case as it may contain unsupported ops in the fallback nor we provide XlaCompiler to the kernel. Also, these patterns are used from a function pass.

This is just an extra check which might be useful if we switch to deny list instead of allow list or avoid crashing if an op with symbol ref is added to the allow list.

The `if num_consumers >= 0:` check causes an error when num_consumers is a Tensor in graph mode:

Previously, we use ICudaEngine::createExecutionContext to create a TensorRT
execution context along with the GPU needed to execute the Cuda Engine. This
API doesn't handle out of GPU memory properly, instead propagates an exception.
This change uses ICudaEngine::createExecutionContextWithoutDeviceMemory to
create a TensorRT execution context without any GPU memory, and let TF-TRT
create the needed GPU memory. In order to keep track of such GPU memory, we
wrap the TensorRT execution context and the associated GPU memory in a new
class callsed ExecutionContext.
